{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_kinard_ver01/data/sn95047246/00529042115/1945092701/0568.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE FOUR\nDept. Commerce\nTo Be Expanded\nWashington, Sept. 20 Secre\ntary of Commerce Wallace today\nannounced a departmental re-or\nganization plan calling for \u201cvigor\nous expansion\u201d of facilities to pro\nmote foreign trade and aid busi\nness\u2014especially small business.\nHe told a press conference that,\nduring reconversion and post-war\nadjustment, the commerce depart\nment \u201cmust be prepared to pull its\nweight in the program of the ad\nministration to assure full profit\nable production and full gainful\nemployment.\u201d\nHe said he would seek three new\nassistant secretaries to be respons\nible for international trade, indus\ntrial economy, and small business.\nThe department now has one as\nsistant secretary for air commerce\nand related technical services.\nProposals have been submitted\nto congress for additional legisla\ntion and funds needed to put the\nprogram into operation, although\nthe department already is in a po\nsition to carry out a substantial\npart of it, he said.\nUnited the suggested program,\nthe department would provide:\n1. A revitalized foreign trade\nservice to cooperate with the state\ndepartment in formulating com-,\nmercial policy and promoting \u201cvig\norously\u201d a high level of foreign\ntrade on a sustained basis.\nIn addition to assisting export\ners and, importers, the department\nwould make recommendations to\nincrease the supply of dollars in\nthe hands of foreign nations on the\ntheory that foreign trade is a \u201ctwo\nway street.\u201d\n2. A strong, balanced program\nto provide business and govern\nment with statistics. This would,\ncenter around a large expansion of J\nthe work of the census bureau-\n3. A complete analytical pro\ngram to give business and govern\nment information on the economic\nsituation and business outlook.\nThis would provide data for shap\ning policies to maintain a high\nlevel of output and employment.\n4. Technological aids and ser\nvices to business, especially small\nbusiness on technical, engineering\nand scientific problems.\n5. Management aids to busi\nness, oriented to the needs of small\nas well as large business.\n6. Strengthening of the techni\ncal service functions of the depart\nment to make them as helpful as\npossible to the nation\u2019s commercial\nand industrial life. This aims to\npromote civil, commercial, and pri\nvate aviation, through the Civil\nAeronautics administration.\nExpansion of the weather bu\nreau and the coast geodetic survey\nis also planned, as well as estab\nlishment of a science advisory\ncommittee to recommend on devel\nopment of scientific activities.\nWallace said it was his intention\nto strengthen the department\u2019s top\npolicy, economic and promotional\npersonnel.\nCAN COMPANY WILL\nSPEND $1,250,000\nON FLORIDA PLANT\nTampa, Fla., Sept. 20 \u2014(Special)\nThe American Can Company today\nannounced additional plans for en\nlargement of its can manufactur\ning plant here, which will bring\nthe total cost of its expansion pro\ngram to $1,250,000.\nThe first part of the program\nannounced several weeks ago, calls\nfor an expenditure of $526,000 ad-!\nditional warehouse space, reloca-{\ntion of shipping facilities and new.\nside tracks.\nThe additional plans announced,\ntoday entail an investment of:\n1550,000. New equipment to be,\ninstalled will cost in excess of;\n^250,000. This second series of ad-,\nditions and new construction will;\ninclude an extension of the main;\nfactory building for handling of;\ntinplate and relocation of the ma\nchine shop, enlargement of the\noffice building and a new structure\nwhich will house the personnel\noffice, employee\u2019s cafeteria and\nlocker rooms, a new closing ma\nchine station and expanded quar\nters for the research department.\nIn making the new addition, C.\nF. Cummings, Jr., superintendent,\nsaid the considerably enlarged\nplant and warehouse facilities ex\npress the company\u2019s faith in a\ngreater future ahead for the citrus\nindustry in the postwar period-\nWhile the Tampa plant at the\ntime of it? erection had a caapcity\nfor can manufacture far beyond\nthe needs of the Florida canning\nindustry, the spectacular accept\nance of citrus products has made\nthese additional facilities neces\nsary, Mr. Cummings said. This\nacceptance, he continued, has come\nabout through the cooperation of\n\u00bboth citrus growers and the can\nning industry; the one has contrib\nuted revolutionary agricultural\nmethods, the other merchandising\nof a high order.\nThe Brooksville Journal is th#\nloader in news. advertising and\ncirculation.\nAHEAD\nAtf GEORGE S. BENSON\nPresident\u2014Warding College\nSea re f. .Arkansas\nGifts of God\nDraw on your imagination for a\nmoment and consider with me an\naltogether improbable circum\nitance. Suppose a well-groomed\ngentleman with an easy flow of lan\nguage should mount an improvised\nplatform in the public square of an\nagricultural county-seat town next\nSaturday afternoon, play a phono\ngraph record through a loud speak\ner to get an audience, and then\nshould say:\n\u201cLadies and Gentlemen\u2014-there is\njust so much- water in the entire\nuniverse; so much and no more. Any\ntime you drink more of it than you\naeed to quench your thirst, you are\ngreedy because some unfortunate\nperson somewhere on earth wants\nwater. He is thirsty. His throat is\ndry and his lips are parching. And\nit is all for want of the water which\nyou so wantonly swallow.\u201d\nIt Is Not True\nSuch a speaker would soon lose\nhis audience. People would walk\naway and leave him. Some of them\nmight think about having his head\nexamined because they know his\n{ideas are out of joint. There is no\nconnection whatever between one\nman\u2019s abundance of water and some\njtar-away stranger\u2019s thirst. The need\nof the sufferer, even if he were a\nvictim of cruelty, is apart from the\nowner of a good well.\nBut the speaker might hold his\naudience if he said something like\nthis: \u201cLadies and Gentlemen\u2014there 1\nis just so much wealth in the world;\nso much and no more. Anybody!\nwith more than he needs for food,\nclothes and shelter is greedy be\ncause there are many people in\nChina and India who never had a\nsquare meal in their lives. They are\npoor because a few people get very\nrich.\u201d\nAnother Fallacy\nThis speech is no nearer true than\nthe one about the water. Both have\nsome facts in them but they are not\nrelated facts. lam not trying to say\nthat wealth is free and cheap like\nwater, but lam saying this: My\nneighbor\u2019s fine home and big car\nhave cost me nothing. He has more\nthan I have because he (or his fa\nther maybe) has more wealth-oreat\ning_ability than I_have.\nFIRST PRESBYTERIAN\nCHURCH\nM. G. Lyerly, Minister.\nThis church will observe Rally\nDay next Sunday morning, Sept.\n30th. An appropriate program xs\n'being prepared for the occasion.\nThe service will begin at 10:30 a.\nm. instead of 10 o\u2019clock.\nAll members of the church and\nSunday school are urged to be\npresent. The Rally Day program\nwill take the place of the regular\npreaching service.\nGARDEN GROVE\nThere will not be preaching ser-\nvices at Scott\u2019s chapel Sunday\nj afternoon. The members have\nvoted to give the pastor a vacation j\non each fifth Sunday.\nThe monthly church night meet-1\ning will be held at the home of Mr.\nand Mrs. Mallory Mondon Thurs\nday night, October 4.\nThe Garden Grove P.-T. A. will\nmeet at the school house Friday\nafternoon, October 5.\nRobert Potter and David Potter,\nwho have spent the summer at the i\nhome of their grandmother, Mrs. i\ni David Ayers, returned Friday to\ntheir home in Tampa.\nMrs. J. C. Kazee, Mrs. Mallory j\nMondon and John Ayers werej\nvisitors to Tampa Thursday.\n1 Jason Gant and Charlie B- Shear\ner were visitors to St. Petersburg\nI Friday.\nI Mrs. Lula Taylor and daughter,\nMrs. Molly Trussle, and children,\nRobert and Myra, of Wauchula. 1\nleft Monday after a visit of several j\ndays at the home of Mrs. Taylor\u2019s\nmother, Mrs. P. W. Mondon. 11\nMiss Theresa Prachar, Tampa, i\nwas visiting her parents, Mr. and;\nMrs. Michael Prachar, Sunday.\nMrs. David Ayers was honored\nlast Thursday on her seventy-fifth:\nbirthday anniversary. She was at\nthe home of Mr. and Mrs. H. T. 11\nHennes where she has been ill. i s\nOnly her children and grandchil- {1\ndren were present, but she was the\nrecipient of many greetings from\nfriends that day.\nI GIiO^LURES... Apply Science to Fishing\nz/|\\V' Instantly Attached to Your Q\nFavorite 8a1t... or Used Alone T\n\u2022No matter where you Hah\u2014in Freeh Or\nSalt water\u2014onee you eeel er troll with a 1 I\nGLOLURE you\u2019ll never be without one. \\\\\\JL\nGLO-LURES retain their highly lomln-\nou for years. Those big shy\nfellows can't resist 'em Way or night. IM\nGat NEW *improved clo-lure\nThousands of enlhu\u00abiaatie fishernsen use x\nand praise C.LO LURES. Start catching\nYOUR limit EVERY lime you neb. Order x k.i\na\u00bb>a>i\u00b0B\u00ab\u2022 GLOLURE today. Only\nOL^LURC CO\u201eD,pt SC,34OS KCtai* St.Chlca,. 13, HL\nTHE BROOKSVILLE JOURNAL. BROOKSVILLE. FLORIDA\nNavy To Hold f\nPacific Bases\n\u2018k.\nWashington, Sept. 20\u2014The navy\ndisclosed today its intention not to\ngive up any Pacific island bases\nuntil a final decision on their dis\nposition is made.\nThe disclosure was made to the\nhouse naval committee by Adm.\nHorne, vice chief of naval opera\ntions.\nThe navy has orders, Adm- Horn\ntold the committee, not to abandon\nany of the bases but to keep them,\nat least in caretake status, until a\nfinal determination is made with\nrespect to what islands the United\nStates shall control permanently.\nAdm. Home and Rear Adm. W.\nL. Burrough submitted to the com\nmittee a list of major and second\nary bases the navy expects to re\ntain permanently after the war.\nAdm. Burrough emphasized that\nthe list was drawn for \u201cplanning\u201d\npurposes only and was tentative\nuntil final arrangements for con\ntrol of the islands are made.\nThe bases tentatively chosen for'\nretention in the Pacific:\nMajor bases: Pearl Harbor,\nGuam-Saipan area, the Philippines,\nManus in the Admiralties.\nSecondary bases: Kodiak, Adak,\nBalboa, Bonins Volcano group,\nRyukyus, Tutu Tawitawi, Subic,\nLeyte-Samar, Palau, Puerto Prin\ncessa, Galapagos, Attu, Johnston\nIsland, Midway, Wake, Samoa, En\ntiwok, Kwajalein, Truk.\nCaretaker emergency bases\nDutch Harbor, Canton Islands,\nPalmyra, Majuro, Ulithi.\nIn the Atlantic, navy plans call\nfor a major base in the Puerto\nRico Virgin islands area, and for\nthese secondary bases:\nArgentina, Bermuda, Guantana\nmo, Trinidad, Coco Solo.\nCaretaker emergency bases in\nthe Atlantic would be located at\nSt. Thomas, Antigua, Georgetown,\nGreat Exuma, Jamaica, and Santa\nlLucia.\nIn continental United States, the\nadmirals disclosed, these facilities\nare planned for the post-war navy:\nFleet operations area: Norfolk-\nHampton Roads Chesapeake bay\narea; New York- Long Island-Nar\nragansett bay-Casco bay area; San\nPedro San Diego ared; Puget\nSound area.\nLAKE LINDSEY^METHODIST\nYOUTH FELLOWSHIP NEWS\nThe M. Y. F. enjoyed the church\nservice of the month, as did all\nmembers. It was held in the grade\nschool auditorium, which was very\nappropriate as Mrs. Milton Ivey;\nwas the \"teacher.\u201d It was a typi\ncal school room, which furnished\nan interesting evening of enter\ntainment not forgetting the two\nbad boys who stood in the corner, i\nWe accepted the invitation to\nScott\u2019s chapel for a Sunday after\nnoon program. It was well ren-!\ndered with Jacqueline Greene as;\nleader. Following that service,\nRev. Ivey invited Mr. Wolf to i\npreach. The sermon was a short!\none and filled with good \u201cfood fox\nth< ugh.\u201d The five cars full re\ntuined happily home.\ne June Hedick has gone to Talia-]\ni 1 hassee where she has enrolled in I\nj college\nOlin Greene S. 1/c. who is now!\nstationed at Jacksonville, camej\nhome for the week-end. He is to i\nlead the young people\u2019s service on;\n1 Sunday evening.\nI Sept. 21 quarterly conference\nwas held in our church. Doctor j\nWaller, the district superintendent,;\nj preached a splendid sermon. Heav- j\nI ily loaded tables were placed under I\nx i the trees and the dinner was great-j\njly enjoyed. Since this was Rev.\nr Ivey\u2019s birthday, his plate contain-\n;led a new suit in the form of bills\nand coins. The card enclosed said,\n\u201cwe love and appreciate our pas\ntor.\u201d\nOlga Bean led the M. Y. F. Sun\n,l day evening with the subject of\n\u201cTithing\u201d brought out in a very\ninteresting manner.\nI j A meeting of officers was held\n11 Monday evening for the purpose of\nI making more interesting, inspiring\nj programs. After the work we had\n11 waffles and hot cakes.\nOur covenant is \u201cTo live clean\ni lives, following the highest we\ni{ know; to give loyalty and service\nto our church; to hold the ideals of\nI unselfish service ever before us.\nstriving continually for human\nbetterment, placing the welfare of\nothers above our own, and in sim\nple trust to follow Jesus as our\nSavior.\u201d\nCLASSIFIED\nFOR SALE\u2014A real buy in a 10-\nacre farm with a 6-room house, 3\nporches, good well of water, also.\nabout 100 fruit trees of nGS7\nPEACHES, ORANGES, PLUMS.\nGRAPES, PECANS, PEARS, PER\nSIMMONS, GRAPEFRUIT; on a\nj county paved road. Price $l5OO.\nSee Raymond Arick, Salesman,\nwith Isom Beasley, Broker, Ph. 53.\nFOR SALE Hickory and hard\nwood for heating. R. H. Ford, rfd\n1, Brooksville, Fla.\ni FOR SALE\u2014A bargain in 50 acres\nof land on hard road about 1^\nmiles from Brooksville. It has\nplenty of yellow pine timber to\nbuild you a nice home and other!\nbuildings that you have been want-!\ning: It is good for fruit, farming, J\nor chickens. Price $3O per acre.\nSee Raymond Arick, Salesman\nwith Isom Beasley, Broker.\nFOR SALE Three good work\nand saddle horses. Fred Aycock,\nShady Rest, Inverness road. RFD\n2, Brooksville, Fla. 4tpd\nFOR SALE\u2014Homes, farms, large\nI or small acreage, city lots, groves,\n'business locations, and apartment\nhouses. We have most anything\n\u0964in Real Estate that you might\nwant. See Raymond Arick, Sales\nman, with Isom Beasley, Broker.\nOver HERNANDO STATE BANK.\nPhone 53.\nFOR SALE One baby buggy,\n$6.00; One play Pen and Pad, $lO\nOne Baby Car Seat, $1.50; Mrs.\nAnn Vanlandingham, 27 Olive St.\nPhone 294-W. 8-2tp\nLOTHER POWER SAW I sell\nthe LOTHER POWER SAW, plen\nty of power, well balanced, mors\npractical for logging, pulp wood\nand farm use than any Saw on the\nmarket. If interested ask for par\nticulars. Reason Henderson. Deal\ner, Lakeland, Ga 8-4tc\nThe Brooksville Journal is the\nleader in news, advertising and;\ncirculation\nP\u00ae*\u00ae is Brandie G^a\u00dfurines^ g\nJhM Establuhed in Eight War Montis g K bn Mb Job* to KM\nal \u00bb\u00bbU9 MlMf tatarf- t>u\u00abta< W torrUta <\u2014t tt baa ban* mM tba tar* eU'l j?**. \u00bbM>oe\u00ab NJM aM UM to\"**\" Ma aaaMablt Maa\nM \u00abwa MH. antH** l \u00bb\u00abMonoM\u00bbW..\u00bbra. .V thaaaalb M mmm. a H purp\u2014aa. M>>l hmTJ X\n8^ M&bhmW\nOf^\nUP AMDDOWN THE COAST LINE\nke J .-.-4\nla^jiihW MHENRYCMDYDREAMED\nNew South, Easily Reconverting,\nSteams Up for Big Industrial Era\nW| Sr MLL BOBING. \u201cThe war has brought a lot oil bar of Commerce, indicated thH)\nO: S \"W Dis\u2019 Th* outh turnin ,h th ^Windurtrieg would be able\nfes uf of iu \u201c\u201coo- into a new era J. o J** \u201c*J\u00a3* to convert from war to neacetima\n11 S d*\u00bb iUty to pSdSS. W. P M PmdStlon Wm on7*^ to\nBl 3 vv-1 a whtchHenry Grady dreamed and to hold ourphu. butto three weeka. However,' the ow\n\u25a0I ,u uu lorward\" *M\u00abh \u00ab\u00abw*l would!\nIQ a Out ot the maw of war It to\nIh.g'SrH I S?XSWT\u201c-X* JOSH\na R li A \"Tvey of southern elUee, ^-.LgS&grY-\u2014C yffim\u00dffr-\ntS Si| i made yesterday by The Constitu- F: V K \u00bbrB\u00bb\u00ab. KSH\u00bbw3\u2022 J\n2\u2014 fi Ph W Hon, reveala that this secUon not aaaeaaaa wm a*\n\u2022S\u2019 .S -LII only la swinging easily into the pe- j A A#;?.--\nW| H 11*11 w riod of transition from war to vm *B^jWggar-\u2018Aa./ \u2018baaue,**^ l\nm ua TT/\u2019 peace, but Is looking upon the re r^-jr-V rHVNTIEH\n*3 3 conversion period as the beginning J .dSj.-}\na *HI r Of Year One in its greater indue- J K\n\u20141 S g 1 trial UN.\n2- jit Perhaps this new apirit-this v. V- y^^4BgSM\u00df3bi\n2m! IH MW trend 01. economy, this new t 1 ~MAW PWflUiHy*-\ns t line of t^lnklng-Ms no better iltaa- A,\u2019 L' Wfedpl\u00ae Attribution facilWkln\ni O H| hr going on tn V he w C\na -Aiigp la.- v\nf i COAST HUB W\n_!=U _\n-fl'r msViho ams\u00abic* s\u2019\n*a \u201cF i e-.-'\n11 0 s%o\u00abn# Dmwai ia Sttfgia !a\na'\u00a7J jl;; For Hone Hsctrical Ajalieaces.\n\\i S S m m Can Use 10,000 More Workers\nK;Sw. T With \u2022\u2022(*rMgL w Btgy W>\u201c \u2019B BBtn w tor MMM Uf* ytaf\u00df \u00ab*rj\u00a3 *r*y If** BP JtM twnto atamlaaan I naaevy aa a whole la w. yt n\n\nTruck Tires\nBecome Short\nApplications Far Outnumber Those\nOn Hand, Chairman Of Local\nRation Board States.\nApplications for new truck tires\nL in Hernando county far outnumber\ni the tires available this month,\nWar Price and Rationing Board\nChairman Otis C. Dick said today.\nAlthough the September tire\nquota for the county is more, Mr.'\nDick pointed out eligible applica-\nI tions have already been received\nor held over from previous months.\nMr. Dick explained that the pent\nup demand for new tires for trucks\nfar exceeds the supply and produc-\nJtion ability of manufacturers even\nI with increased production sched\nI ules for the next few months.\nj Local boards are still operating\ni on a quota basis, he continued.\nProof of tire need certified by\nofficial OPA inspection station.\nTires that will stand recapping and\nrepair will not be replaced by new\ntires.\nQuota limitations:\nI Tire conservation must continue'\nto be practiced fh every way by the j\nmotorist, with recapping still urged\nas the number one solution for,\nmost drivers.\nr it\n>OTJCE OF APITICATION\nFOR TAX DEED\n(Senate Bill No. 163)\nNOTICE IS HEREBY GIVEN. That\nH. B. Montgomery, holder of Tax Cer- I\ntlflcate No. 4SI. issued the Ist. day of\nAugust. A. I'. 1932: Tax Certificate No.\n2701. issued the 7th. day of August, A.\nD. 1933. has filed same in my office and\nhas made application for a tax deed to\nbe issued thereon.\nSaid certificate embraces the follow\nj ing described property in the County\nof Hernando. State of Florida, to-wit:\nNorthwest Quarter of the Northeast\nI i Quarter (Less 4 acres iu NE Corner)\n1 Section 33. Tfiownship 22 South. Range\n;20 East, containing 36 acres, more or\nI less.\nJ The assessment of the said property\nj under the said certificates issued was\niu the name of W. N. McElveen and W.\ni L. MW\u2019er.\n\u2018j Cnless said certificates snail he re\ndoomed according to law. the property j\ndescribed therein will be sold to the i\nhighest bidder at the court house door J\n\u2022>n the first Monday in the month of\n1 October. 1945. which is the first day of\nOctobt r. 1945.\ni Dated this third day of September,\n1945.\n\u2019Seal) H. C. MICKLER,\nClerk Circuit Court. Hernando\nCounty. Florida.\nBy PREMIA VOGEL. Deputy Clerk.\nSALE OF COUNTY LANDS\nNOTICE is hereby given that the\nfollowing described lands owned bv\nHernando County. Florida, will be sold\nat public outcry, to the highest bidder\nfor cash, at the west door of the court\nhouse in Brooksville, Florida, begin\nning at the hour of 11 ;Oo o\u2019clock A M\nEastern War Time, on October 8. 1945'\n(15298) From a point 110 ft.\n4 inches west of N.\nLine of Bay Port\nroad with W. prop\nerty line of Howell\nAve., where the prop\nerties now owned by\nStandard Oil Co. and\nS. R. Collins join,\nrun thence North 102-\n.75 ft. to the North\nline of old concrete\nwall, thence East 48\nft. along N. line of\nsaid wall, thence\nsoutherly parallel to\nthe E. line of said\nCollins, thence West\n48 ft. to point of be\nginning. Howell Es\ntate Division, City of\nBrooksville, as per\nDemi Book 60. page\n161 22 22 19\nBids start at 1257.35.\n(15299)\u2014 E% of SE% of NEU\nof SW% -..15 21 19\nBids start at $36.00.\n(15300)\u2014EU of NW% of SWU\nof SWU 33 21 19\nBlds start, at $20.00.\n(15301)-SWU of NWU ..6 23 19\nBids start at 1107.25.\n(15302)-Lot 16. of Highland\nPark Addition to the\nCity of Brokaville ..22 22 19\nBids start at $23.00.\n(15303)-EU of S% of NEU\nof NEU 21 22 19\nBids start at $26.00.\nh.\u2018>3O4)-WU of SWU of\nSWU of NWU.. -.21 22 21\nBids start at $16.00.\n15305)-W% of NEU G 22 18\nFids start nt $127.25.\n(15306) WU of EU of NWU\nof SWU 25 22 18\nBlds start at $36.60.\n115:10\"' W!4 of EL, of NWU\nof SEU 26 22 18\nBids start at $36.00.\n(1530!\u00bbi Lots 7 and 8. Emer\nson\u2019s sub-division of\nBlock 23 of Hale\u2019s\nAddition to Brooks\nville 22 22 19\nBlds start at $207.45.\n(Seal) H. C.-MTCKLER.\nClerk Circuit Court. Hernando\nCounty, Florida.\nBy PHEMIA VwGEL. Denuty Clerk.\nDale of first publication. Sept. 20. 1945.\nHERNANDO BUSINESS COL\nLEGE, INC., opens October Ist,\nat 7:30 p. m. Murphy Building.\nThe Brooksville Journal is the\nleader in news, advertising and\ncirculation.\nTuhrsday, September 27, 1945\nFIRST BAPTIST CHURCH\nRev. Arvcl G. Miller, Pastor.\nSunday school, 9:4e m.. C. M.\nEmerson, Superintendent.\nThis church is open at all times\nfor prayer and meditation.\nUnion Young People\u2019s Servic^\n7:00 p. m.\nMorning worship. 11:00 a. m.\nEvening service, 8:00.\nTraining Union, 6:45 p. m., Miss\nNancy Keathley, Director.\n1 Wednesday, mid-week prayer\n1 and praise service, 8:00 p. m.\nEveryone welcome to every ser-\nI vice.\n\nI SCHEDULE OF CATHOLIC r\nSERVICES\nSt. Anthony\u2019s Brooksville: Mass\n\u2018each Sunday and Holy Day of\nObligation, 9 a. m.\nSt. Mary\u2019s, Masaryktown: Mass\neach Sunday and Holy Day of\nObligation, 10:30 a. m.\nSt. Stanislaus, Hammock: Mass\nevery other Sunday, 10:30 a. m.\nRev. James Hoge, 0.5.8., pastor,\nfrom St. Leo Abbey.\na I\nCHURCH OF GOD\nSunday school at 10 a. m.\nSermon, 11 a. m., and 8 p. m.\nYoung People\u2019s service, Sunday,\n/:00 p. m.\nW. M. RUMLER, Pastor.\nFIRST METHODIST CHURCH\nRev. R. P. Marshall, Pastor.\nT. S. Rice, Church School Super\nintendent\nSunday School for all ages at\n9:45 a. m.\nj Morning worship, 11:00.\nNOTICE OF APPLICATION\nFOR TAX DEED\n(Senate Bill No. 16S)\nNOTICE IS HEREBY GIVEN. That\nMunuel Johnson, holder of Tax Certifi\ncate No. 452, issued the First day of\nJune. A. D. 1943, has filed same in\nmy office and has made application for\na tax deed to be issued thereon.\nSaid certificate embraces the follow\nIng described property in the County\ni of Hernando. State of Florida, to-wit:\nSaxon\u2019s Sub Addition to Brooksville.\nW^ of Lot 5, See DB 42, page 149,\nBlock 3. Section 22, Township 22 South,\nRange 19 East.\nThe assessment of the said property\nunder the said certificate issued was in\nthe name of Francis J. McKee.\nUnless said certificate shall bo re\ndeemed according to law. the property t\ndescribed therein will be sold to the\nhighest bidder at the court house uuor\non the first Monday in the month of\nOctober. 1945. which is the First day\nof October, 1945.\nDated this 29th day of August, 1945.\n(Seal) 11. C. MICKLER,\nClerk Circuit Court. Hernando\nCounty. Florida.\nBy PHEMIA VOGEL, Deputy Clerk.","height":"20668","width":"14800"}}
